In whole though, the more older, the faster the time. Think about it. Take your parents for example. They always say, “your growing so fast!” But when you’re an adult, people go like oh you look the same.
For example (this quote is from my music teacher)
Take a child like Franny, who is 5
And Casey, 38 years old
Franny like 5 years from now, she’ll look quite different.
Then Casey, 38. 5 years from now, he won’t look so much different. (No offense Casey)
Because kids grow, it’s the sad truth about having children.
So moral of the story......



LIFE IS FAST AND APPRECIATE IT!!!!!!!
We all need to listen to Casey and our elders. Who have some sense

snippet.textDisplay:
Life doesn't get any shorter or longer. It's just way we are enjoying it, or waste it.

When I was a kid (here we go...) I tend to play, enjoy time with friends, family, etc.
Now at 40, most of my time I was on computer or android.
That's the real time killer.

How do I know the time is same length when I was a kid?
When it's blackout. You'll feel time longer because you got nothing to do.
So unless your gadget is making money, stay away from it.

Life is this freight train. It leaves the station slowly, but it picks up momentum and it goes faster and faster and faster. Then you wake up one day and it’s 2020 and you’re not a kid anymore. You’ve become that adult that you remember when you were a kid, you remember looking at, thinking; I’ll never be that old. But you will be that old and there’s nothing; there’s nothing; you can do to change that. -Casey Neistat 2020

Realest thing I’ve ever heard.

snippet.textDisplay:
Wow, thanks for the reminder. You’re like a modern day Socrates the way you can communicate these thoughts that I imagine everyone has had to deal with through the ages.
Waking up New Years morning and taking my 85yr old mother to hospital due to a heart attack was a mortality reality check for me.
I think I’ve thought to much about the future and aspirations of wealth for most of my life, but where do I find myself? Looking at the reality of life, realizing today is the most important day.
I can’t look back and say what if I’d gotten of my backside ages ago to do what I love. I just have to do it today and continue to do it. That’s where contentment exists.
Then when I get to the stage of life that my mother is at now, I’ll be satisfied that I did my best and brought happiness to others. Thanks Casey.
